	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Clock ticking on Jamaican sugar sector diversification  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												27 April 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The chairperson of the Sugar Association of the Caribbean, Karl James, has warned that if the Jamaican sugar sector cannot move into increased production of value-added products, “it will not survive” much beyond 2020. He maintained that since “there is going to be a reduction in the price of bulk sugar”, creative ways will need to be found to add value to bulk sugar. According to Mr James, given the existence of a regional market for refined sugar products, “the establishment of a refinery is one crucial component of Jamaica's survival.”</p><p>The Jamaican Permanent Secretary for Agriculture, Donovan Stanberry, has stressed the critical importance of moving “into the by-products of sugar cane”, in order to fully exploit the commercial potential of sugar cane to generate multiple revenue streams. He warned that Jamaica is “not likely” ever again to enjoy the high sugar prices from which it currently benefits, commenting that the current supply arrangements have only “one year remaining”. According to press reports, Jamaica is now in the second year of a 3-year deal with Tate &amp; Lyle to supply sugar at approximately US$894/tonne. Mr Stanberry also highlighted the importance of reducing the costs and improving the efficiency of current sugar sector operations.</p><p>A former director of the Factories Services Division of the Sugar Industry Research Institute of Jamaica has commented that “Jamaica must now act quickly to save this important industry or our role in sugar will only be a part of history in the very near future.”</p><p>Just how far revenue diversification can go in the sugar sector is illustrated by the announcement in January 2014 from Royal Cosun, the Dutch sugar farmers’ cooperative, of a joint venture with Belgian sugar producer Finsucre and Amsterdam-based chemical company Avantium to develop bioplastics from sugar beet. According to Rabobank, “bioplastics show the highest growth projections when it comes to demand for EU sugar, with a CAGR [compound annual growth rate] of up to 40%; higher than the 5% expected in bioethanol and the flat outlook for food markets.” Rabobank maintains that “as competition in EU sugar and starch markets is expected to increase after 2017, a diversified strategy could be important for companies in these sectors.”&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Jamaica Gleaner</i>, ‘From a king to a pauper!’, 2 March 2014</p><p>
<a href="http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20140302/news/news3.html " target="_self">http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20140302/news/news3.html</a></p><p><i>Foodqualitynews.com</i>, ‘Sugar and starch producers cash in on Bioplastics’, 28 January 2014, 
<a href="http://www.foodqualitynews.com/Innovation/Sugar-and-starch-producers-cash-in-on-bioplastics" target="_self">http://www.foodqualitynews.com/Innovation/Sugar-and-starch-producers-cas...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The bio-plastics option being explored by Royal Cosun takes sugar sector diversification to a new level, beyond the value-added refining, ethanol, bio-gas, fertiliser, chemicals, and co-generated electricity being attempted by the most advanced of the ACP sugar diversification programmes in Mauritius (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Getting-ahead-of-policy-change-Lessons-from-the-Mauritian-sugar-experience" target="_blank">Getting ahead of policy change: Lessons from the Mauritian sugar experience</a>’, 28 January 2013). In view of the progress being made in Mauritius and elsewhere, the need for the Jamaican sugar sector to act is clearly urgent, particularly when one bears in mind the long lead time for the design and implementation of such investments. In Mauritius, for example, the process of revenue diversification was initiated as early as 2000, with many of these revenue streams only beginning to approach their realisable potential by 2013.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
